Incorrect. Australia has no interest in making an example of him one way or another. Tennis Australia tried to help him weasel his way into the country and they failed. The federal government did its job even though it became quite messy, but Tennis Australia should he wearing all of that blowback, not the Australian Government.

It's also worth noting that while the ATAGI advice may have stated that a prior infection was a legitimate reason not to get vaccinated, it is not a valid reason to gain entry to Australia without quarantine. The document you showed was a department of health document not a department of immigration document and when I checked the immigration requirements, a previous infection was NOT grounds for entry and he knew that as of November 2021 as outlined in your video. 

The reasons given by the Minister for cancelling his visa were such that he had to make sure the court could not overturn the decision again. The legislation doesn't include as one of the reasons that a person hasn't satisfied the entry conditions.

Having said all the above, it's also worth noting that unvaccinated people can still come to Australia with 14 days of quarantine. If he was really interested in playing by the rules, he wouldn't have tried to subvert them in the first place, do the 14 days quarantine and then play in the tournament. But no, he tried to scam his way in with the help of Tennis Australia and challenge the border officials and Australian Government in court to play. 

He's not interested in playing by the rules when it comes to this and that's been blindingly apparent. He expects people to treat him differently just because he can hit a tennis ball well. It's an appalling attitude and I would laugh my head off if he decided to get vaccinated after all.

snippet.textDisplay:
Excellent video! Well rounded and covering many details.

However, it contains a couple of grievous errors pertaining to Djokovic's infection that paints him in a worse light, which is pretty crucial to get right on such a sensitive subject:
1) According to his statement, he had tested negative with two rapid antigen-tests before attending the event with the kids. It was his positive PCR-test, which takes much longer to process, that he did not see the results from until after the event.
2) In the image of photographs with dates that you show a couple of times, the dates of the interview and the kids event seem switched, making it look like he attended the more crowded event later, after receiving the positive test result. I know you say differently in the video.

I would have also liked a bit more of an emphasis on the ruling of the last appeal. It surprised me that the judge said that they had only made a judgement on the legality and not the merit of the immigration minister's decision, effectively saying that they did not care about the reasoning behind the decision, only if he had made any legal errors in executing his power, meaning that there really was no case from the start. This was different to what everyone had lead me to believe.

There was also the case of some saying that his test result was faked. I never got into that, but would like a quick overview of that situation. That would be very damning for Djokovic, but I heard on say it was refuted.

snippet.textDisplay:
A fantastic video once again that summarises the whole saga in just under 13 minutes - I was really looking forward to this one.
As a tennis fan (particularly a Fed fan) I think the whole debacle was a huge shame that could have the potential to alter the GOAT race - it just was not good for Tennis as a sport. 
As a defending champion, world number one of a major sport and 9 time Australian Open Singles winner - they really should have found a way for him to enter the tournament. 
Based on the way Nadal played, and his record against Djokovic on hard court, I don't think Nadal would have won the title this year if Djokovic were able to participate in this tournament.

As for Djokovic, I find it very hard to believe he actually had COVID if you look at his activities in December 2021 and also the test ID sequences (all very questionable). He also had plenty of time to decide to get vaccinated to avoid this whole scenario but he chose not to, he made his personal choice as an adult despite the possible outcome. And as many viewers here would already know, Djokovic is no stranger to controversy and he's made many questionable decisions (e.g. Adria Tour, PTPA, refusing to admit he needed to change his on-court behaviour eventually leading to his default at the US Open, his stubborn refusal to get elbow surgery and crying for days after the surgery - which by the way after that he's won 8 slams out of 10 finals). A lot of NoleFam fans are bitter at Australia about his treatment. Yes the detention and handling by Australia was terrible, but they need to remember that Novak made his decision not to take the vaccine and it was his choice, other Serbian players participated in Australia without any issues. For some of his supporters to portray him as someone who is standing up for the oppressed, let's set the record straight, Novak is a guy who has benefitted and earnt more career prize money than any other players in the history of the sport.

From the Australian Federal Government and Victorian State Government perspective - this whole saga exposed some serious problems and it was heavily-politicised. Ultimately the Federal Government managed the borders and they had the right to deport Djokovic, but it also exposed their incompetence and the treatment of refugees in detention. The Victorian State Government got cold feet and in particular Jaala Pulford deserves a special mention. She did not shy away from the fact she was a big Nadal fan and wanted him to win (and I think there can be very little doubt she did not want Djokovic to get in his way) - they were the ones who pulled the rug under Djokovic - because the state government was working with Tennis Australia in creating the medical exemption panels (they created this process and when pressured withdrew their support when pressured by the Federal Government). There is simply no way Djokovic would have flown to Melbourne knowing he would be detained. It also yet again exposed how different levels of government were not working or effectively talking with each other.

Regarding Tennis Australia - they were warned by the Federal Government previously that vaccination was mandatory and yet they still proceeded with the medical panel. The medical exemption panel process was also questionable particularly the dates/timeline - as another post pointed out the discrepancy between the application due date and Djokovic's submission. Djokovic was allowed to make his submission around a week past the due date.

Lastly about the vaccination requirements to enter the tournament - this policy made sense when Delta was the most common strain in Australia, but Omicron had become the dominant strain in late December and January, and it's fairly evident that the current vaccines have reduced efficacy on Omicron. We've already seen vaccinated players having COVID infections (particularly those who participated at the Abu Dhabi exhibition events). How could anyone reasonably assert Djokovic could pose a serious threat on public health when Victoria was having thousands of new cases daily during this period?  Australians have a strong belief that everyone should be made to comply to the same rules (e.g. no special treatment for celebrities etc.), however we are talking about a very significant global event here, if they can't work their way around this and make special arrangements / dispensations, it really leads me to question whether they are competent enough to host this event.
